data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert count explicitly — failure shows "expected 3 but got X"
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert all active — CollectionAssert for condition on each element
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | `Assert.IsTrue(cond, "message")` | Always add a message for LINQ predicates |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent and failure output |
| — | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, item)` | For reference/value checks |
| — | `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` | Same items, any order |
| — | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` | Same items, same order |

**Tip:** If you want richer fluent assertions (`.Should().HaveCount(3).And.OnlyContain(…)`), consider the **FluentAssertions** NuGet package — it's very popular with MSTest.
